Note:
PowerShell Parser - AST construction for PowerShell scripts

This file provides complete syntax analysis for PowerShell scripts.
Constructs an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) representing the script structure.

Features:
- Complete PowerShell grammar support
- Commands and pipelines
- Control structures (if, while, for, foreach, switch)
- Function and filter definitions
- Variable assignments and references
- Object-oriented features (classes, methods)
- Parameter declarations
- Try-catch-finally blocks
- Cmdlet invocations with parameters
- Array and hashtable literals
- Subexpressions and operators

Dependencies:
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
- frontends/powershell/powershell_lexer.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/powershell/powershell_lexer.runa" as Lexer

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Node Types
Note: ============================================================================

Constant AST_SCRIPT as Integer is 1                     Note: Top-level script
Constant AST_COMMAND as Integer is 2                    Note: Simple command/cmdlet
Constant AST_PIPELINE as Integer is 3                   Note: Pipeline (cmd1 | cmd2)
Constant AST_STATEMENT_LIST as Integer is 4             Note: Statement list (; separated)
Constant AST_BLOCK as Integer is 5                      Note: { statements }

Note: Control Structures
Constant AST_IF_STATEMENT as Integer is 10              Note: if-elseif-else
Constant AST_WHILE_STATEMENT as Integer is 11           Note: while loop
Constant AST_FOR_STATEMENT as Integer is 12             Note: for loop
Constant AST_FOREACH_STATEMENT as Integer is 13         Note: foreach loop
Constant AST_SWITCH_STATEMENT as Integer is 14          Note: switch statement
Constant AST_DO_WHILE as Integer is 15                  Note: do-while loop
Constant AST_DO_UNTIL as Integer is 16                  Note: do-until loop

Note: Function and Class Definitions
Constant AST_FUNCTION_DEFINITION as Integer is 20       Note: function definition
Constant AST_FILTER_DEFINITION as Integer is 21         Note: filter definition
Constant AST_WORKFLOW_DEFINITION as Integer is 22       Note: workflow definition
Constant AST_CLASS_DEFINITION as Integer is 23          Note: class definition
Constant AST_ENUM_DEFINITION as Integer is 24           Note: enum definition
Constant AST_METHOD_DEFINITION as Integer is 25         Note: method definition
Constant AST_PROPERTY_DEFINITION as Integer is 26       Note: property definition

Note: Parameters and Variables
Constant AST_PARAM_BLOCK as Integer is 30               Note: param() block
Constant AST_PARAMETER as Integer is 31                 Note: Parameter declaration
Constant AST_VARIABLE as Integer is 32                  Note: $variable
Constant AST_VARIABLE_ASSIGNMENT as Integer is 33       Note: $var = value
Constant AST_PROPERTY_ACCESS as Integer is 34           Note: $obj.property
Constant AST_METHOD_CALL as Integer is 35               Note: $obj.method()
Constant AST_ARRAY_ACCESS as Integer is 36              Note: $array[index]

Note: Expressions
Constant AST_BINARY_EXPRESSION as Integer is 40         Note: Binary operation
Constant AST_UNARY_EXPRESSION as Integer is 41          Note: Unary operation
Constant AST_SUBEXPRESSION as Integer is 42             Note: $()
Constant AST_ARRAY_SUBEXPRESSION as Integer is 43       Note: @()
Constant AST_HASHTABLE as Integer is 44                 Note: @{}
Constant AST_ARRAY_LITERAL as Integer is 45             Note: @(1,2,3)
Constant AST_TYPE_EXPRESSION as Integer is 46           Note: [type]

Note: Exception Handling
Constant AST_TRY_STATEMENT as Integer is 50             Note: try block
Constant AST_CATCH_STATEMENT as Integer is 51           Note: catch block
Constant AST_FINALLY_STATEMENT as Integer is 52         Note: finally block
Constant AST_THROW_STATEMENT as Integer is 53           Note: throw statement

Note: Flow Control
Constant AST_RETURN_STATEMENT as Integer is 60          Note: return statement
Constant AST_BREAK_STATEMENT as Integer is 61           Note: break statement
Constant AST_CONTINUE_STATEMENT as Integer is 62        Note: continue statement
Constant AST_EXIT_STATEMENT as Integer is 63            Note: exit statement

Note: Literals and Identifiers
Constant AST_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 70                Note: Simple identifier
Constant AST_CMDLET as Integer is 71                    Note: Cmdlet name
Constant AST_STRING_LITERAL as Integer is 72            Note: String literal
Constant AST_NUMBER_LITERAL as Integer is 73            Note: Numeric literal
Constant AST_BOOLEAN_LITERAL as Integer is 74           Note: Boolean literal
Constant AST_NULL_LITERAL as Integer is 75              Note: $null literal

Note: Special Constructs
Constant AST_SWITCH_CLAUSE as Integer is 80             Note: Switch case clause
Constant AST_CASE_LABEL as Integer is 81                Note: Case label
Constant AST_DEFAULT_CLAUSE as Integer is 82            Note: Default clause
Constant AST_REDIRECTION as Integer is 83               Note: Output redirection
Constant AST_COMMENT as Integer is 84                   Note: Comment

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser State Structure
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Parser state layout:
Note: Offset 0: lexer (lexer pointer)
Note: Offset 8: current_token (current token index)
Note: Offset 16: tokens (token array pointer)
Note: Offset 24: token_count (number of tokens)
Note: Offset 32: has_error (error flag)

@Reasoning:
Allocates a 40-byte arena-backed parser record. Reads the token array
and count from the lexer to support index-based iteration; current_token
starts at 0 (first token).
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_parser" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new PowerShell parser

    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with 40
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, lexer

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    Let token_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, 0      Note: current_token
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, tokens
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, token_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 32, 0     Note: has_error

    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the token-type tag of the current token, or TOKEN_EOF if the
index has run past the end. Saves callers from index/array math.
@End Reasoning
Process called "current_token_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token type

    Let current_index be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let token_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 24

    If current_index is greater than or equal to token_count:
        Return TOKEN_EOF from Lexer
    End If

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
    Let token_offset be current_index multiplied by 32
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with tokens plus token_offset, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the owned lexeme (exact source text) of the current token, or
the empty string when the index has run past the end. Each token slot
is 32 bytes (type @0, lexeme @8, start_pos @16, line @24); the lexeme
was sliced from the source at tokenize time so it survives for the
lifetime of the parse. Content-bearing productions call this to attach
names / literal values / operators to the AST node value slot.
@End Reasoning
Process called "current_token_lexeme" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token's source lexeme

    Let current_index be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let token_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 24

    If current_index is greater than or equal to token_count:
        Return ""
    End If

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
    Let token_offset be current_index multiplied by 32
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with tokens plus token_offset, 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
Sets the value/data slot (offset 32) of an AST node to the supplied
lexeme. Centralises the node-content write so every production records
its source text identically and the node layout stays in one place.
@End Reasoning
Process called "set_node_value" takes node as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Store a lexeme (name / literal / operator) in the node value slot

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, value
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Variable and parameter lexemes are captured WITH their leading sigil
($ for variables, - for parameters) because that is how the lexer
slices them from source. The HIR backend re-adds the sigil when it
emits (emit_variable prepends $, emit_parameter prepends -), so the
stored name must be the bare form. This helper returns an owned copy
of the lexeme with its first byte removed; an empty or single-byte
lexeme yields the empty string.
@End Reasoning
Process called "strip_first_char" takes lexeme as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return the lexeme with its leading sigil byte removed

    If lexeme is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Let len be proc string_length from StringCore with lexeme
    If len is less than or equal to 1:
        Return ""
    End If
    Return proc string_substring from StringPrim with lexeme, 1, len minus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Increments the current_token index. Token array is pre-tokenised so
advance is constant time with no lexer interaction.
@End Reasoning
Process called "advance_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next token

    Let current_index be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, current_index plus 1
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Required-token consumption: advances on match, sets the parser's
has_error flag and returns 0 on mismatch. Used to enforce mandatory
syntax positions (e.g., closing parens).
@End Reasoning
Process called "expect_token" takes parser as Integer, expected as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Expect specific token type and advance

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If current_type is equal to expected:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Set error flag
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 32, 1
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Non-consuming check: returns 1 if current token matches expected, 0
otherwise. Use match for optional-token decisions; use expect when
the token must appear.
@End Reasoning
Process called "match_token" takes parser as Integer, expected as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current token matches expected type

    Let current_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    Return current_type is equal to expected
End Process

@Reasoning:
Allocates a 48-byte AST node. Layout: type@0, parent@8, children@16,
child_count@24, data@32, capacity@40. The children buffer is grown lazily
by add_child, which doubles capacity and copies on overflow so arbitrarily
large statement bodies are supported with amortised O(1) appends.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Heap-allocated node; nodes live until the parse run completes. The capacity
slot tracks the current children-buffer length so add_child can detect when
it must reallocate to a larger buffer.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_ast_node" takes node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new AST node with type

    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with 48
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, 0         Note: parent
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 0        Note: children
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 0        Note: child_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 0        Note: data
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, 0        Note: capacity

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Appends child to parent.children, lazily allocating an 8-slot children
buffer on first append and doubling its capacity (copying the existing
entries into the larger buffer) whenever the count reaches the current
capacity. This supports statement bodies of any size with amortised O(1)
appends. Also sets child.parent for upward traversal.
@End Reasoning
Process called "add_child" takes parent as Integer, child as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add child node to parent

    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 24
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 16
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 40

    If children is equal to 0:
        Let initial_capacity be 8
        Let buffer_bytes be initial_capacity multiplied by 8
        Set children to proc allocate from Layout with buffer_bytes
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 16, children
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 40, initial_capacity
        Set capacity to initial_capacity
    End If

    If child_count is greater than or equal to capacity:
        Let new_capacity be capacity multiplied by 2
        Let new_bytes be new_capacity multiplied by 8
        Let new_children be proc allocate from Layout with new_bytes
        Let copy_bytes be child_count multiplied by 8
        proc memory_copy from Layout with new_children, children, copy_bytes
        Set children to new_children
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 16, children
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 40, new_capacity
        Set capacity to new_capacity
    End If

    Let child_offset be child_count multiplied by 8
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with children plus child_offset, 0, child
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent, 24, child_count plus 1

    Note: Set parent pointer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with child, 8, parent

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
PowerShell treats newlines as statement separators, but they're noise in
many positions (after braces, semicolons, etc.). This helper consumes
the run of TOKEN_NEWLINE so parsers can call it once at decision points.
@End Reasoning
Process called "skip_newlines" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip newline tokens

    While proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_NEWLINE from Lexer is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Top-level entry: produces a SCRIPT AST node containing the sequence of
statements. Newlines between statements are absorbed by skip_newlines.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_script" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse top-level PowerShell script

    @Reasoning:
    PowerShell script consists of statements separated by newlines or semicolons.
    Handle empty scripts and optional trailing separators.
    @End Reasoning

    Let script be proc create_ast_node with AST_SCRIPT

    proc skip_newlines with parser

    While proc current_token_type with parser is not equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
        Let stmt be proc parse_statement with parser
        If stmt is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with script, stmt
        End If

        Note: Skip statement separators (newlines and semicolons). The loop
        Note: terminates as soon as the current token is neither separator,
        Note: which guarantees forward progress even when parse_statement
        Note: failed to consume a token.
        Let scanning_separators be 1
        While scanning_separators is equal to 1:
            Let token_type be proc current_token_type with parser
            If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NEWLINE from Lexer:
                proc advance_token with parser
            Otherwise:
                If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
                    proc advance_token with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Set scanning_separators to 0
                End If
            End If
        End While

        Note: Forward-progress guard: if the statement parser consumed no
        Note: tokens and no separator was present, advance once so the outer
        Note: loop cannot spin forever on an unrecognised token.
        If stmt is equal to 0:
            If proc current_token_type with parser is not equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
                proc advance_token with parser
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return script
End Process

@Reasoning:
Statement dispatcher routing if/while/for/foreach/switch/do/try/throw/
return/break/continue/exit/function/filter/workflow/class/enum/param
based on the leading token. Falls through to pipeline parsing for
expression statements and command pipelines.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse PowerShell statement

    @Reasoning:
    PowerShell statements can be:
    - Control structures (if, while, for, foreach, switch)
    - Function/class definitions
    - Try-catch blocks
    - Simple commands or pipelines
    - Variable assignments
    @End Reasoning

    proc skip_newlines with parser
    Let token_type be proc current_token_type with parser

    Note: Control structures
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IF from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_if_statement with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_WHILE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_while_statement with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FOR from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_for_statement with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FOREACH from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_foreach_statement with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_SWITCH from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_switch_statement with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DO from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_do_statement with parser
    End If

    Note: Function and class definitions
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FUNCTION from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_function_definition with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FILTER from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_filter_definition with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_WORKFLOW from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_workflow_definition with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_CLASS from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_class_definition with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ENUM from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_enum_definition with parser
    End If

    Note: Exception handling
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_TRY from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_try_statement with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_THROW from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_throw_statement with parser
    End If

    Note: Flow control
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_RETURN from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_return_statement with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_BREAK from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_break_statement with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_CONTINUE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_continue_statement with parser
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EXIT from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_exit_statement with parser
    End If

    Note: Parameter block
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PARAM from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_param_block with parser
    End If

    Note: Comments
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_COMMENT from Lexer or token_type is equal to TOKEN_BLOCK_COMMENT from Lexer:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Return proc create_ast_node with AST_COMMENT
    End If

    Note: Default: try to parse as pipeline or command
    Return proc parse_pipeline with parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
"if (cond) { body } elseif (cond) { ... } else { ... }" - PowerShell
if/elseif/else chain. Conditions are expressions; bodies are blocks.
The elseif chain is unrolled into a list of (cond, body) pairs.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_if_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse if-elseif-else statement

    @Reasoning:
    PowerShell if statement syntax:
    if (condition) { statements }
    elseif (condition) { statements }
    else { statements }
    @End Reasoning

    Let if_stmt be proc create_ast_node with AST_IF_STATEMENT

    Note: Parse 'if'
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_IF from Lexer

    Note: Parse condition (with or without parentheses)
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer
    Let condition be proc parse_expression with parser
    If condition is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with if_stmt, condition
    End If
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer

    Note: Parse if body
    Let if_body be proc parse_block with parser
    If if_body is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with if_stmt, if_body
    End If

    Note: Parse elseif clauses
    While proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_ELSEIF from Lexer is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser

        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer
        Let elseif_condition be proc parse_expression with parser
        If elseif_condition is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with if_stmt, elseif_condition
        End If
        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer

        Let elseif_body be proc parse_block with parser
        If elseif_body is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with if_stmt, elseif_body
        End If
    End While

    Note: Parse else clause
    If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_ELSE from Lexer is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let else_body be proc parse_block with parser
        If else_body is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with if_stmt, else_body
        End If
    End If

    Return if_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
"while (cond) { body }" - pre-condition loop. Condition is parenthesised
(unlike C-style "while cond"), matching PowerShell grammar.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_while_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse while loop

    @Reasoning:
    PowerShell while loop syntax:
    while (condition) { statements }
    @End Reasoning

    Let while_stmt be proc create_ast_node with AST_WHILE_STATEMENT

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_WHILE from Lexer

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer
    Let condition be proc parse_expression with parser
    If condition is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with while_stmt, condition
    End If
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer

    Let body be proc parse_block with parser
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with while_stmt, body
    End If

    Return while_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
"for ($init; $cond; $update) { body }" - C-style three-part for loop.
Each clause is optional (PowerShell allows empty init/cond/update).
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_for_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse for loop

    @Reasoning:
    PowerShell for loop syntax:
    for ($i = 0; $i -lt 10; $i++) { statements }
    @End Reasoning

    Let for_stmt be proc create_ast_node with AST_FOR_STATEMENT

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_FOR from Lexer

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer

    Note: Parse initialization
    Let init be proc parse_expression with parser
    If init is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with for_stmt, init
    End If
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer

    Note: Parse condition
    Let condition be proc parse_expression with parser
    If condition is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with for_stmt, condition
    End If
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer

    Note: Parse increment
    Let increment be proc parse_expression with parser
    If increment is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with for_stmt, increment
    End If

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer

    Let body be proc parse_block with parser
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with for_stmt, body
    End If

    Return for_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
"foreach ($var in $collection) { body }" - iterator-style loop, distinct
from C-style for. The "-parallel" modifier is captured as an attribute
when present (PowerShell workflow context).
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_foreach_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse foreach loop

    @Reasoning:
    PowerShell foreach loop syntax:
    foreach ($item in $collection) { statements }
    @End Reasoning

    Let foreach_stmt be proc create_ast_node with AST_FOREACH_STATEMENT

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_FOREACH from Lexer

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer

    Note: Parse loop variable
    Let loop_var be proc parse_expression with parser
    If loop_var is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with foreach_stmt, loop_var
    End If

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_IN from Lexer

    Note: Parse collection
    Let collection be proc parse_expression with parser
    If collection is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with foreach_stmt, collection
    End If

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer

    Let body be proc parse_block with parser
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with foreach_stmt, body
    End If

    Return foreach_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
"switch [-options] (expr) { clauses }" - PowerShell switch is more
powerful than C (regex matching, wildcards, file input). Options like
-regex/-wildcard/-exact are attributes; clauses are pattern -> body pairs.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_switch_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse switch statement

    @Reasoning:
    PowerShell switch statement syntax:
    switch ($expression) {
        value1 { statements }
        value2 { statements }
        default { statements }
    }
    @End Reasoning

    Let switch_stmt be proc create_ast_node with AST_SWITCH_STATEMENT

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_SWITCH from Lexer

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer
    Let expression be proc parse_expression with parser
    If expression is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with switch_stmt, expression
    End If
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LBRACE from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Note: Parse switch clauses
    Let switch_scanning be 1
    While switch_scanning is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current is equal to TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer:
            Set switch_scanning to 0
        Otherwise:
            If current is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
                Set switch_scanning to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let before_index be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
                Let clause be proc parse_switch_clause with parser
                If clause is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_child with switch_stmt, clause
                End If
                proc skip_newlines with parser
                Let after_index be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
                If after_index is equal to before_index:
                    proc advance_token with parser
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer

    Return switch_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
"pattern { body }" - one clause within a switch. The pattern may be a
literal, regex, wildcard, or "default" depending on the switch options.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_switch_clause" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse switch case clause

    Let clause be proc create_ast_node with AST_SWITCH_CLAUSE

    Note: Check for default case
    If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer is equal to 1:
        Note:
        Each token slot is 32 bytes (type @0, lexeme @8, start_pos @16,
        line @24). We read the start_pos and compare the seven source bytes
        there against "default", also requiring the following byte to be a
        non-identifier character so that names such as "defaultValue" do not
        match. The source pointer is reached via parser -> lexer (parser
        offset 0) -> source (lexer offset 0).
        :End Note
        Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
        Let current_index be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Let token_offset be current_index multiplied by 32
        Let token_ptr be tokens plus token_offset
        Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token_ptr, 16

        Let lexer_state be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
        Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer_state, 0
        Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer_state, 8

        Note:
        Reuse the lexer's position-based comparator to test the seven bytes
        at start_pos against "default" (case-insensitive, matching
        PowerShell keyword semantics), then enforce a word boundary so a
        longer identifier like "defaultValue" is not misclassified.
        :End Note
        Let word_matches be proc match_operator_exact from Lexer with source, start_pos, 7, "default"
        Let is_default be 0
        If word_matches is equal to 1:
            Let boundary_index be start_pos plus 7
            If boundary_index is greater than or equal to source_length:
                Set is_default to 1
            Otherwise:
                Let boundary_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, boundary_index
                If proc is_identifier_char from Lexer with boundary_char is equal to 0:
                    Set is_default to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If is_default is equal to 1:
            Note: This is a default case, create DEFAULT node
            Let default_node be proc create_ast_node with AST_DEFAULT_CLAUSE
            proc add_child with clause, default_node
            proc advance_token with parser
        Otherwise:
            Note: Regular case value expression
            Let case_value be proc parse_expression with parser
            If case_value is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with clause, case_value
            End If
        End If

    Otherwise:
        Note: Regular case value
        Set case_value to proc parse_expression with parser
        If case_value is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with clause, case_value
        End If
    End If

    Note: Parse case body
    Let body be proc parse_block with parser
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with clause, body
    End If

    Return clause
End Process

@Reasoning:
"do { body } while/until (cond)" - post-condition loop. PowerShell has
both do-while (loop while true) and do-until (loop until true) variants;
we dispatch by which keyword follows the body.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_do_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse do-while or do-until statement

    @Reasoning:
    PowerShell do statement syntax:
    do { statements } while (condition)
    do { statements } until (condition)
    @End Reasoning

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_DO from Lexer

    Let body be proc parse_block with parser

    Let token_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_WHILE from Lexer:
        Let do_while be proc create_ast_node with AST_DO_WHILE
        If body is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with do_while, body
        End If

        proc advance_token with parser  Note: skip 'while'
        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer
        Let condition be proc parse_expression with parser
        If condition is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with do_while, condition
        End If
        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer

        Return do_while

    Otherwise:
        Note: Assume do-until
        Let do_until be proc create_ast_node with AST_DO_UNTIL
        If body is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with do_until, body
        End If

        Note: Skip optional 'until' keyword
        If proc current_token_type with parser is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If

        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer
        Set condition to proc parse_expression with parser
        If condition is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with do_until, condition
        End If
        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer

        Return do_until
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
"function Name [(params)] { body }" - top-level function. Parameter
list can use parentheses or the param() block syntax inside the body;
both forms are normalised to the same parameter-list AST.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_function_definition" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse function definition

    @Reasoning:
    PowerShell function syntax:
    function Name { param() statements }
    function Name ($param1, $param2) { statements }
    @End Reasoning

    Let func_def be proc create_ast_node with AST_FUNCTION_DEFINITION

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_FUNCTION from Lexer

    Note: Parse function name. Verb-Noun function names (Get-Greeting,
    Note: Set-Config) lex as TOKEN_CMDLET because they contain a hyphen, so
    Note: both identifier and cmdlet name tokens are accepted here.
    Let fname_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If fname_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer or fname_type is equal to TOKEN_CMDLET from Lexer:
        Let name_node be proc create_ast_node with AST_IDENTIFIER
        Let name_lexeme be proc current_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_value with name_node, name_lexeme
        proc add_child with func_def, name_node
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse optional parameter list
    If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let param_list be proc parse_parameter_list with parser
        If param_list is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with func_def, param_list
        End If
        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer
    End If

    Note: Parse function body
    Let body be proc parse_block with parser
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with func_def, body
    End If

    Return func_def
End Process

@Reasoning:
"filter Name { body }" - a PowerShell filter is a function variant
that processes pipeline input one element at a time. Distinguished
from a function only by the keyword and the implicit $_ binding.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_filter_definition" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse filter definition

    Let filter_def be proc create_ast_node with AST_FILTER_DEFINITION

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_FILTER from Lexer

    Note: Parse filter name
    If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer is equal to 1:
        Let name_node be proc create_ast_node with AST_IDENTIFIER
        Let name_lexeme be proc current_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_value with name_node, name_lexeme
        proc add_child with filter_def, name_node
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse filter body
    Let body be proc parse_block with parser
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with filter_def, body
    End If

    Return filter_def
End Process

@Reasoning:
"workflow Name { body }" - PowerShell workflow (V3+) supports parallel
execution and checkpointing. Lowered to a function with workflow=true
attribute since downstream HIR doesn't distinguish them structurally.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_workflow_definition" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse workflow definition

    Let workflow_def be proc create_ast_node with AST_WORKFLOW_DEFINITION

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_WORKFLOW from Lexer

    Note: Parse workflow name
    If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer is equal to 1:
        Let name_node be proc create_ast_node with AST_IDENTIFIER
        Let name_lexeme be proc current_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_value with name_node, name_lexeme
        proc add_child with workflow_def, name_node
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse workflow body
    Let body be proc parse_block with parser
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with workflow_def, body
    End If

    Return workflow_def
End Process

@Reasoning:
"class Name [: Base, ...] { members }" - PowerShell 5+ class. Members
include properties, methods, constructors, and static variants. Multi-
inheritance through interfaces in the base list.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_class_definition" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse class definition

    @Reasoning:
    PowerShell class syntax:
    class ClassName {
        [type] $property
        ClassName($param) { }
        [type] Method($param) { }
    }
    @End Reasoning

    Let class_def be proc create_ast_node with AST_CLASS_DEFINITION

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_CLASS from Lexer

    Note: Parse class name
    If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer is equal to 1:
        Let name_node be proc create_ast_node with AST_IDENTIFIER
        Let name_lexeme be proc current_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_value with name_node, name_lexeme
        proc add_child with class_def, name_node
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse class body
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LBRACE from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Let class_scanning be 1
    While class_scanning is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current is equal to TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer:
            Set class_scanning to 0
        Otherwise:
            If current is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
                Set class_scanning to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let before_index be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
                Let member be proc parse_class_member with parser
                If member is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_child with class_def, member
                End If
                proc skip_newlines with parser
                Let after_index be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
                If after_index is equal to before_index:
                    proc advance_token with parser
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer

    Return class_def
End Process

@Reasoning:
Class-body member dispatcher. Routes property, method, constructor, and
static members based on the leading modifiers and structure (type
annotation followed by name vs paren-list).
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_class_member" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse class member (property or method)

    Let token_type be proc current_token_type with parser

    Note: Check for type annotation
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LBRACKET from Lexer:
        Note: Type annotation - could be property or method
        Return proc parse_typed_member with parser
    End If

    Note: Check for constructor (class name)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Note: Could be constructor or method
        Return proc parse_method_or_constructor with parser
    End If

    Note: Variable assignment (property)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_VARIABLE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_property_definition with parser
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
"[Type] $name [= default]" property OR "[Type] Name(params) { body }"
method. Resolves the ambiguity by lookahead after the type/name pair:
( means method, anything else means property.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_typed_member" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse typed member (with [type] annotation)

    Note: Parse type annotation
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LBRACKET from Lexer
    Let type_expr be proc parse_type_expression with parser
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RBRACKET from Lexer

    Let token_type be proc current_token_type with parser

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_VARIABLE from Lexer:
        Note: Typed property
        Let prop_def be proc create_ast_node with AST_PROPERTY_DEFINITION
        If type_expr is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with prop_def, type_expr
        End If

        Let var_node be proc parse_variable with parser
        If var_node is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with prop_def, var_node
        End If

        Return prop_def
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Note: Typed method
        Let method_def be proc create_ast_node with AST_METHOD_DEFINITION
        If type_expr is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with method_def, type_expr
        End If

        Let name_node be proc create_ast_node with AST_IDENTIFIER
        Let name_lexeme be proc current_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_value with name_node, name_lexeme
        proc add_child with method_def, name_node
        proc advance_token with parser

        Note: Parse parameter list
        If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Let param_list be proc parse_parameter_list with parser
            If param_list is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with method_def, param_list
            End If
            proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer
        End If

        Note: Parse method body
        Let body be proc parse_block with parser
        If body is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with method_def, body
        End If

        Return method_def
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
"Name(params) { body }" - method (or constructor when Name equals the
enclosing class name). The parser doesn't compare names here; the
semantic analyser classifies them later based on context.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_method_or_constructor" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse method or constructor

    Let method_def be proc create_ast_node with AST_METHOD_DEFINITION

    Note: Parse method name
    Let name_node be proc create_ast_node with AST_IDENTIFIER
    Let method_name_lexeme be proc current_token_lexeme with parser
    proc set_node_value with name_node, method_name_lexeme
    proc add_child with method_def, name_node
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Parse parameter list
    If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let param_list be proc parse_parameter_list with parser
        If param_list is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with method_def, param_list
        End If
        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer
    End If

    Note: Parse method body
    Let body be proc parse_block with parser
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with method_def, body
    End If

    Return method_def
End Process

@Reasoning:
"$name [= default]" property without type annotation. Used when
parse_typed_member sees no leading type expression. Default value is
optional; absent means uninitialised.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_property_definition" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse property definition

    Let prop_def be proc create_ast_node with AST_PROPERTY_DEFINITION

    Let var_node be proc parse_variable with parser
    If var_node is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with prop_def, var_node
    End If

    Note: Parse optional assignment
    If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_ASSIGN from Lexer is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let value be proc parse_expression with parser
        If value is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with prop_def, value
        End If
    End If

    Return prop_def
End Process

@Reasoning:
"enum Name { Member1 [= value], Member2, ... }" - PowerShell 5+ enum.
Backing type is Int32 by default; values are auto-incrementing unless
explicitly assigned.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_enum_definition" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse enum definition

    Let enum_def be proc create_ast_node with AST_ENUM_DEFINITION

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_ENUM from Lexer

    Note: Parse enum name
    If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer is equal to 1:
        Let name_node be proc create_ast_node with AST_IDENTIFIER
        Let name_lexeme be proc current_token_lexeme with parser
        proc set_node_value with name_node, name_lexeme
        proc add_child with enum_def, name_node
        proc advance_token with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse enum body
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LBRACE from Lexer
    proc skip_newlines with parser

    Let enum_scanning be 1
    While enum_scanning is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current is equal to TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer:
            Set enum_scanning to 0
        Otherwise:
            If current is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
                Set enum_scanning to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let before_index be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

                Note: Parse enum member
                If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer is equal to 1:
                    Let member_node be proc create_ast_node with AST_IDENTIFIER
                    Let member_lexeme be proc current_token_lexeme with parser
                    proc set_node_value with member_node, member_lexeme
                    proc add_child with enum_def, member_node
                    proc advance_token with parser

                    Note: Parse optional value assignment
                    If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_ASSIGN from Lexer is equal to 1:
                        proc advance_token with parser
                        Let value be proc parse_expression with parser
                        If value is not equal to 0:
                            proc add_child with member_node, value
                        End If
                    End If
                End If

                Note: Skip optional comma
                If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer is equal to 1:
                    proc advance_token with parser
                End If

                proc skip_newlines with parser

                Let after_index be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
                If after_index is equal to before_index:
                    proc advance_token with parser
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RBRACE from Lexer

    Return enum_def
End Process

@Reasoning:
"try { body } catch [Type] { ... } [finally { ... }]" - multiple
catch clauses supported each with optional exception-type filter.
Finally is optional but if present must come last.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_try_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse try-catch-finally statement

    @Reasoning:
    PowerShell try statement syntax:
    try { statements }
    catch [ExceptionType] { statements }
    finally { statements }
    @End Reasoning

    Let try_stmt be proc create_ast_node with AST_TRY_STATEMENT

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_TRY from Lexer

    Note: Parse try body
    Let try_body be proc parse_block with parser
    If try_body is not equal to 0:
        proc add_child with try_stmt, try_body
    End If

    Note: Parse catch blocks
    While proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_CATCH from Lexer is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser

        Let catch_block be proc create_ast_node with AST_CATCH_STATEMENT

        Note: Parse optional exception type
        If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_LBRACKET from Lexer is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Let exception_type be proc parse_type_expression with parser
            If exception_type is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with catch_block, exception_type
            End If
            proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RBRACKET from Lexer
        End If

        Note: Parse catch body
        Let catch_body be proc parse_block with parser
        If catch_body is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with catch_block, catch_body
        End If

        proc add_child with try_stmt, catch_block
    End While

    Note: Parse finally block
    If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_FINALLY from Lexer is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser

        Let finally_block be proc create_ast_node with AST_FINALLY_STATEMENT
        Let finally_body be proc parse_block with parser
        If finally_body is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with finally_block, finally_body
        End If

        proc add_child with try_stmt, finally_block
    End If

    Return try_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
"throw [expr]" - expression is optional ("throw" alone re-throws the
current exception in a catch block). PowerShell accepts any value to
throw, not just Exception subclasses.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_throw_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse throw statement

    Let throw_stmt be proc create_ast_node with AST_THROW_STATEMENT

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_THROW from Lexer

    Note: Parse optional expression
    Let token_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_NEWLINE from Lexer and token_type is not equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
        Let expression be proc parse_expression with parser
        If expression is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with throw_stmt, expression
        End If
    End If

    Return throw_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
"return [expr]" - PowerShell return is mostly cosmetic since the
function's output is the value of its last expression; explicit returns
still set the output value. Optional expression handled with lookahead.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_return_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse return statement

    Let return_stmt be proc create_ast_node with AST_RETURN_STATEMENT

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RETURN from Lexer

    Note: Parse optional expression
    Let token_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If token_type is not equal to TOKEN_NEWLINE from Lexer and token_type is not equal to TOKEN_SEMICOLON from Lexer:
        Let expression be proc parse_expression with parser
        If expression is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with return_stmt, expression
        End If
    End If

    Return return_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
"break [label]" - terminates the innermost loop or labeled loop. Label
is optional and is typically a string for break-to-label semantics.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_break_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse break statement

    Let break_stmt be proc create_ast_node with AST_BREAK_STATEMENT
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_BREAK from Lexer
    Return break_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
"continue [label]" - skips to the next loop iteration. Like break, can
target a labeled outer loop when needed.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_continue_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse continue statement

    Let continue_stmt be proc create_ast_node with AST_CONTINUE_STATEMENT
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_CONTINUE from Lexer
    Return continue_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
"exit [code]" - terminates the PowerShell script with the given exit
code (default 0). Distinct from return because it leaves the entire
script, not just the current function.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_exit_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse exit statement

    Let exit_stmt be proc create_ast_node with AST_EXIT_STATEMENT

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_EXIT from Lexer

    Note: Parse optional exit code
    Let token_type be proc current_token_type with parser
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_NUMBER from Lexer:
        Let exit_code be proc parse_expression with parser
        If exit_code is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with exit_stmt, exit_code
        End If
    End If

    Return exit_stmt
End Process

@Reasoning:
"param([attrs] [Type]$Name = default, ...)" block - the in-body
parameter declaration form. Each parameter can carry attributes
(e.g., [Parameter(Mandatory)], [ValidateSet(...)]) before the type.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_param_block" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse param() block

    Let param_block be proc create_ast_node with AST_PARAM_BLOCK

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_PARAM from Lexer
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LPAREN from Lexer

    Note: Parse parameter list
    Let param_scanning be 1
    While param_scanning is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current is equal to TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer:
            Set param_scanning to 0
        Otherwise:
            If current is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
                Set param_scanning to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let before_index be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
                Let param be proc parse_parameter_declaration with parser
                If param is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_child with param_block, param
                End If

                Note: Skip optional comma
                If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer is equal to 1:
                    proc advance_token with parser
                End If
                proc skip_newlines with parser

                Let after_index be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
                If after_index is equal to before_index:
                    proc advance_token with parser
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer

    Return param_block
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single parameter inside a param block: optional attribute list,
optional type annotation, mandatory $name, optional default value.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_parameter_declaration" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse parameter declaration

    Let param_decl be proc create_ast_node with AST_PARAMETER

    Note: Parse optional type annotation
    If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_LBRACKET from Lexer is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let type_expr be proc parse_type_expression with parser
        If type_expr is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with param_decl, type_expr
        End If
        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RBRACKET from Lexer
    End If

    Note: Parse parameter variable
    If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_VARIABLE from Lexer is equal to 1:
        Let var_node be proc parse_variable with parser
        If var_node is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with param_decl, var_node
        End If
    End If

    Note: Parse optional default value
    If proc match_token with parser, TOKEN_ASSIGN from Lexer is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token with parser
        Let default_value be proc parse_expression with parser
        If default_value is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with param_decl, default_value
        End If
    End If

    Return param_decl
End Process

@Reasoning:
"(param1, param2, ...)" - the parenthesised parameter list for function
declarations. Each parameter follows the same grammar as param-block
entries but without the [Parameter()] attribute prefix.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_parameter_list" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse comma-separated parameter list

    Let param_list be proc create_ast_node with AST_PARAM_BLOCK

    Let plist_scanning be 1
    While plist_scanning is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc current_token_type with parser
        If current is equal to TOKEN_RPAREN from Lexer:
            Set plist_scanning to 0
        Otherwise:
            If current is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
                Set plist_scanning to 0
            Otherwise:
                Let before_index be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
                Let param be proc parse_parameter_declaration with parser
